00:10:16.580 --> 00:10:18.630
to consult their phone
than a sales associate.

00:10:18.630 --> 00:10:20.780
So even when they
walk into a store,

00:10:20.780 --> 00:10:23.360
the first thing that they do
is they look at their phone,

00:10:23.360 --> 00:10:24.710
rather than ask for help.

00:10:24.710 --> 00:10:27.010
And in fact people
will say, is there

00:10:27.010 --> 00:10:28.260
something I can help you with?

00:10:28.260 --> 00:10:28.450
Can I help you?

00:10:28.450 --> 00:10:29.210
And they say, oh no no.

00:10:29.210 --> 00:10:29.810
No thanks.

00:10:29.810 --> 00:10:31.268
And there they are,
on their phone.

00:10:31.268 --> 00:10:33.634
So what do you suggest?

00:10:33.634 --> 00:10:35.800
How do you think you can
use that to your advantage?

00:10:35.800 --> 00:10:38.070
Or how could a retailer use
that to their advantage,

00:10:38.070 --> 00:10:39.920
rather than it being
something that's

00:10:39.920 --> 00:10:42.885
coming between the customer?

00:10:42.885 --> 00:10:44.931
STEVEN ALAN: I mean,
that's definitely something

00:10:44.931 --> 00:10:45.680
that we're seeing.

00:10:45.680 --> 00:10:47.055
People are coming
into the store,

00:10:47.055 --> 00:10:49.730
and they're definitely trying
to get more information

00:10:49.730 --> 00:10:51.646
on products while
they're in the store.

00:10:51.646 --> 00:10:53.270
And I think in the
future, whether it's

00:10:53.270 --> 00:10:58.040
QR codes or something, where you
can actually really do a deeper

00:10:58.040 --> 00:11:01.180
dive-- Because I think that even
the people working in the store

00:11:01.180 --> 00:11:02.730
have a limited amount
of information.

00:11:02.730 --> 00:11:04.980
But what you can
actually-- you can videos.

00:11:04.980 --> 00:11:10.830
You can do anything,
depending on the product.

00:11:10.830 --> 00:11:12.220
LISA GREEN: Maybe
Brett, maybe we

00:11:12.220 --> 00:11:14.890
can loop you into to the
conversation a little bit,

00:11:14.890 --> 00:11:16.480
in terms of, what
brands do you think

00:11:16.480 --> 00:11:18.200
are doing interesting
things with all

00:11:18.200 --> 00:11:21.620
of these-- the direction
that shopping is moving in?

00:11:21.620 --> 00:11:23.617
Have you seen
anything interesting?

00:11:23.617 --> 00:11:26.200
BRETT HEYMAN: Well, I myself am
obsessed with personalisation.

00:11:26.200 --> 00:11:28.175
Like, we launched
our website mid-June.

00:11:28.175 --> 00:11:30.800
And we have a bespoke component
where you can type in your name

00:11:30.800 --> 00:11:32.258
and see how it
would look on a bag.

00:11:32.258 --> 00:11:34.140
And so I would love to
develop that further.

00:11:34.140 --> 00:11:35.960
And so in that
vein, I'm obsessed

00:11:35.960 --> 00:11:38.760
with the Nike interface,
when you can do the bespoke.

00:11:38.760 --> 00:11:41.380
But I also love how
Warby Parker does

00:11:41.380 --> 00:11:44.700
the-- you can upload your
face and try on the glasses

00:11:44.700 --> 00:11:46.050
virtually.

00:11:46.050 --> 00:11:48.730
It is my dream to have a virtual
dressing room for my body,

00:11:48.730 --> 00:11:50.730
and just have your
body up there,

00:11:50.730 --> 00:11:53.047
and have your virtual
clothes, and never ever ever

00:11:53.047 --> 00:11:54.588
have to try on
anything in real time.

00:11:54.588 --> 00:11:55.397
[LAUGHTER]

00:11:55.397 --> 00:11:56.730
LISA GREEN: What about you guys?

00:11:56.730 --> 00:11:59.520
Have you seen anything, any
brands that you would call out

00:11:59.520 --> 00:12:01.892
as doing anything
really interesting?

00:12:01.892 --> 00:12:03.142
LEAH CHERNIKOFF: I don't know.

00:12:03.142 --> 00:12:05.610
Nothing comes to mind for me.

00:12:05.610 --> 00:12:09.350
LAUREN SHERMAN: I think Nike and
personalization stuff is cool.

00:12:09.350 --> 00:12:12.890
I mean, I think there
are the obvious ones.

00:12:12.890 --> 00:12:17.250
Burberry and you know, that
get called out again and again

00:12:17.250 --> 00:12:17.920
and again.

00:12:17.920 --> 00:12:22.130
But I think, there's a brand
in the UK called "Matches."

00:12:22.130 --> 00:12:23.020
They sell a lot.

00:12:23.020 --> 00:12:24.730
They have a huge
presence online.

00:12:24.730 --> 00:12:27.470
But they sell a lot of-- they
have a bunch of boutiques.

00:12:27.470 --> 00:12:30.180
They sell really
expensive clothes.

00:12:30.180 --> 00:12:33.490
And they have a thing.

00:12:33.490 --> 00:12:36.020
They sell tons of SKUs online.

00:12:36.020 --> 00:12:37.070
Tons of denim.

00:12:37.070 --> 00:12:38.810
Tons of contemporary.

00:12:38.810 --> 00:12:42.661
So most of you work, I
think, in ad, fashion ads,

00:12:42.661 --> 00:12:44.160
so you probably
know contemporaries,

00:12:44.160 --> 00:12:45.320
like mid-price stuff.

00:12:45.320 --> 00:12:47.680
But they don't have much
of that in the boutique,

00:12:47.680 --> 00:12:49.679
because they don't have
a lot of square footage.

00:12:49.679 --> 00:12:52.570
They only have dressed
that are $1,000 or more.

00:12:52.570 --> 00:12:55.770
So when they're in the
store, they have iPads out.

00:12:55.770 --> 00:12:59.200
And they're kind of
training their probably very

00:12:59.200 --> 00:13:03.270
well-paid customer service
people to kind of loop

00:13:03.270 --> 00:13:04.990
in the stuff on the iPad.

00:13:04.990 --> 00:13:09.394
And anecdotally, they've
told me that a lot of people

00:13:09.394 --> 00:13:10.810
who have never
bought stuff online

00:13:10.810 --> 00:13:14.960
before are buying jeans through
them, or a pair of earrings,

00:13:14.960 --> 00:13:17.250
or something like that,
while they're in the store.

00:13:17.250 --> 00:13:21.690
So I think that kind of
stuff, it's still clunky.

00:13:21.690 --> 00:13:24.150
And it's not where
it needs to be.

00:13:24.150 --> 00:13:29.590
But the more that happens,
the more exciting shopping

00:13:29.590 --> 00:13:31.595
is going to become.

00:13:31.595 --> 00:13:34.776
LISA GREEN: And a little bit
in the personalization vein,

00:13:34.776 --> 00:13:36.400
we were discussing
a little bit earlier

00:13:36.400 --> 00:13:38.340
that, I read an
article this morning

00:13:38.340 --> 00:13:42.710
about how big data can really
play a role in personalization.

00:13:42.710 --> 00:13:46.390
The article was about this
guy who had received an email

00:13:46.390 --> 00:13:48.499
to install solar
panels on his home.

00:13:48.499 --> 00:13:49.790
But it was really personalized.

00:13:49.790 --> 00:13:54.590
The company had used the
Google Maps technology

00:13:54.590 --> 00:13:57.970
and overlaid their own
API, whatever they did.

00:13:57.970 --> 00:14:00.970
And they said they found
that this guy's house was

00:14:00.970 --> 00:14:03.250
perfect for installing
solar panels.

00:14:03.250 --> 00:14:04.530
And so the email said that.

00:14:04.530 --> 00:14:05.946
It said, we've
done some research.

00:14:05.946 --> 00:14:08.270
And your house is
great for solar panels.

00:14:08.270 --> 00:14:09.280
And he clicked on it.

00:14:09.280 --> 00:14:11.840
And the link brought him to
another personalized place

00:14:11.840 --> 00:14:14.180
that had Google Earth imagery.

00:14:14.180 --> 00:14:16.770
And said, here's what we would
do with your solar panels.

00:14:16.770 --> 00:14:18.350
And the next clip
was to a rep, who

00:14:18.350 --> 00:14:20.380
already had all his
information and was ready.

00:14:20.380 --> 00:14:22.500
He didn't have to say anything.

00:14:22.500 --> 00:14:25.520
It was such a powerful
way to use data,

00:14:25.520 --> 00:14:27.826
instead of it just
being, oh, well

00:14:27.826 --> 00:14:28.950
you bought a pair of jeans.

00:14:28.950 --> 00:14:30.400
So you should buy more jeans.

00:14:30.400 --> 00:14:31.850
Here's 30% off.

00:14:31.850 --> 00:14:34.840
What do you guys think could
be done in the fashion space

00:14:34.840 --> 00:14:37.695
with all this data that
we now have access to?

00:14:41.415 --> 00:14:44.180
STEVEN ALAN: I think
that it's interesting.

00:14:44.180 --> 00:14:46.890
Because I was just
in L.A. last weekend.

00:14:46.890 --> 00:14:49.720
And I started getting
emails-- and I'm not even sure

00:14:49.720 --> 00:14:52.820
how this was done, but--
I started getting emails

00:14:52.820 --> 00:14:57.250
for companies that
had L.A. stores,

00:14:57.250 --> 00:15:00.570
but where I never received
the emails from those stores.

00:15:00.570 --> 00:15:02.476
I don't even know how they knew.

00:15:02.476 --> 00:15:06.200
I was just thinking about that.

00:15:06.200 --> 00:15:10.100
But I think that-- Definitely,
like for example right now,

00:15:10.100 --> 00:15:12.100
another initiative
is, if you come

00:15:12.100 --> 00:15:14.230
into the store as
a customer, you

00:15:14.230 --> 00:15:17.280
have your history of what
you've bought from the store.

00:15:17.280 --> 00:15:20.030
And then we have a history
of what you've bought online.

00:15:20.030 --> 00:15:22.110
But the sales
associates can't really

00:15:22.110 --> 00:15:23.740
access what you've
bought online, yet.

00:15:23.740 --> 00:15:25.050
I mean, they will be able to.

00:15:25.050 --> 00:15:27.880
But I think that is
really important,

00:15:27.880 --> 00:15:31.140
to be able to see sort
of a complete profile.

00:15:31.140 --> 00:15:34.430
And another thing that
we're going to be using

00:15:34.430 --> 00:15:37.650
is a technology called
Digital Marvels or Touche.

00:15:37.650 --> 00:15:39.215
I'm not sure which company.

00:15:39.215 --> 00:15:40.090
But it's interesting.

00:15:40.090 --> 00:15:42.710
What they do is,
they allow the person

00:15:42.710 --> 00:15:46.460
who's at the store to be
able to sort of drag and drop

00:15:46.460 --> 00:15:47.170
very easily.

00:15:47.170 --> 00:15:50.380
So if you're a customer, and
you want to find out information

00:15:50.380 --> 00:15:53.420
on a particular brand-- you're
interested in acne, say,

00:15:53.420 --> 00:15:55.070
now what's happening
is you might

00:15:55.070 --> 00:16:00.820
get an email with a couple links
on different items, whatever.

00:16:00.820 --> 00:16:03.020
But with this, you'd could
actually get-- I mean,

00:16:03.020 --> 00:16:03.520
it's an app.

00:16:03.520 --> 00:16:04.920
You'd have to download the app.

00:16:04.920 --> 00:16:08.177
But then it would just be
really easy for the associate

00:16:08.177 --> 00:16:09.760
to just sort of drag
a bunch of things

00:16:09.760 --> 00:16:11.460
that they think that you
might be interested in.

00:16:11.460 --> 00:16:13.250
And then you could
drag a bunch of things

00:16:13.250 --> 00:16:15.380
out that you're
not interested in.

00:16:15.380 --> 00:16:18.215
It just really facilitates
a great experience.

00:16:23.926 --> 00:16:24.800
LAUREN SHERMAN: Yeah.

00:16:24.800 --> 00:16:27.280
I'm actually working on a
story about this right now.

00:16:27.280 --> 00:16:31.600
And I think Gilt does a
really interesting job

00:16:31.600 --> 00:16:32.510
with this stuff.

00:16:32.510 --> 00:16:35.329
They have a ton
of people working

00:16:35.329 --> 00:16:36.370
on their personalization.

00:16:36.370 --> 00:16:40.835
They have a huge team of
engineers working on it.

00:16:40.835 --> 00:16:44.050
And I think that they've
actually done the best job.

00:16:44.050 --> 00:16:45.910
You know, they
think about climate.

00:16:45.910 --> 00:16:47.420
They think about where you are.

00:16:47.420 --> 00:16:48.930
They think of your size.

00:16:48.930 --> 00:16:51.550
And they really try
to whittle it down.

00:16:51.550 --> 00:16:54.600
So you get an email that
is only the products

00:16:54.600 --> 00:16:55.660
that you'd actually want.

00:16:55.660 --> 00:16:56.521
Does it always work?

00:16:56.521 --> 00:16:57.020
No.

00:16:57.020 --> 00:16:59.480
But they're doing
interesting things with.

00:16:59.480 --> 00:17:02.710
And I think also it
can help in the buying

00:17:02.710 --> 00:17:06.339
process for a lot
of big retailers.

00:17:06.339 --> 00:17:09.010
The way that
retailers buy things

00:17:09.010 --> 00:17:11.660
is kind of very-- they
look at past data.

00:17:11.660 --> 00:17:13.990
And now they'll be able
to look current data,

00:17:13.990 --> 00:17:18.599
and say, oh, people
across the internet

00:17:18.599 --> 00:17:21.329
are buying green
shirts or whatever.

00:17:21.329 --> 00:17:22.960
Maybe we should
order or we should

00:17:22.960 --> 00:17:25.220
get some green shirts
made, things like that.

00:17:25.220 --> 00:17:27.180
So I think there's a
lot of different ways

00:17:27.180 --> 00:17:28.190
it can be applied.

00:17:28.190 --> 00:17:33.040
Some of them, it might
not be worth all the time

00:17:33.040 --> 00:17:35.000
and effort, the end result.

00:17:35.000 --> 00:17:37.200
But I think,
especially if you're

00:17:37.200 --> 00:17:42.450
a big, big multi-brand website,
to be able to kind of figure

00:17:42.450 --> 00:17:45.130
out what's available in
people's sizes, in the things

00:17:45.130 --> 00:17:47.850
that they'd already
like, is exciting.

00:17:47.850 --> 00:17:53.390
And the better that they get
at it, the more-- I guess,

00:17:53.390 --> 00:17:55.000
the less people
will even notice,

00:17:55.000 --> 00:17:58.337
or, hopefully it will
result in better sales.

00:17:58.337 --> 00:17:59.545
LEAH CHERNIKOFF: [INAUDIBLE].

00:18:02.980 --> 00:18:03.780
LISA GREEN: OK.

00:18:03.780 --> 00:18:06.120
So what about shifting
gears a little bit?

00:18:06.120 --> 00:18:07.270
What about social?

00:18:07.270 --> 00:18:11.840
What platforms do you think
are really making a difference?

00:18:11.840 --> 00:18:15.100
I think that what
we see is brands

00:18:15.100 --> 00:18:18.115
are really going after
kind of every platform.

00:18:18.115 --> 00:18:18.990
They're on Pinterest.

00:18:18.990 --> 00:18:19.630
They're on Instagram.

00:18:19.630 --> 00:18:19.950
They're on YouTube.

00:18:19.950 --> 00:18:20.820
They're on Facebook.

00:18:20.820 --> 00:18:24.632
And in fact, their marketing has
every little icon next to it.

00:18:24.632 --> 00:18:26.090
Which ones do you
guys really think

00:18:26.090 --> 00:18:29.720
are actually having an
influence, driving purchase?

00:18:29.720 --> 00:18:31.540
And as a brand,
which ones do you

00:18:31.540 --> 00:18:33.990
feel like you are best
able to sort of communicate

00:18:33.990 --> 00:18:35.153
your own messaging from?

00:18:35.153 --> 00:18:39.090
And from where you guys sit,
which brands-- what's working

00:18:39.090 --> 00:18:42.097
and why?

00:18:42.097 --> 00:18:43.555
STEVEN ALAN: I mean
for us, I would

00:18:43.555 --> 00:18:46.880
say Instagram is probably
the most effective.

00:18:46.880 --> 00:18:48.050
Because it's just so visual.

00:18:50.960 --> 00:18:54.840
I think that we can sort of
connect the dots with Instagram

00:18:54.840 --> 00:18:56.230
better than anything else.

00:18:56.230 --> 00:19:00.080
And then with Instagram, goes
to Twitter, goes to Facebook.

00:19:00.080 --> 00:19:01.560
So it's very strong.

00:19:01.560 --> 00:19:04.800
We're about to launch another
app called Spring, which

00:19:04.800 --> 00:19:07.390
will be-- I think
it's going to be very

00:19:07.390 --> 00:19:09.760
significant in
the fashion space.

00:19:09.760 --> 00:19:15.620
Because it will actually be
a shoppable visual platform.

00:19:15.620 --> 00:19:19.765
So I think I'm
excited about that.

00:19:19.765 --> 00:19:22.974
BRETT HEYMAN: For us also,
Instagram's the most important.

00:19:22.974 --> 00:19:25.140
Being a small brand, and
just communicating directly

00:19:25.140 --> 00:19:27.000
with the customers,
anytime I post a picture

00:19:27.000 --> 00:19:28.290
that people like that,
I have so many people

00:19:28.290 --> 00:19:29.720
asking if we'll ship to Mexico?

00:19:29.720 --> 00:19:31.260
If we'll ship here,
and how much bags are.

00:19:31.260 --> 00:19:33.218
So I can directly interface
with the customers.

00:19:33.218 --> 00:19:36.146
And I get so many screenshots
of an Instagram post

00:19:36.146 --> 00:19:37.520
sent back to our
customer service

00:19:37.520 --> 00:19:38.540
saying we want to
order this bag.

00:19:38.540 --> 00:19:39.581
Where do we get this bag?

00:19:39.581 --> 00:19:40.312
So it's great.

00:19:40.312 --> 00:19:42.520
And then if there were ever--
if we want to do sales,

00:19:42.520 --> 00:19:45.000
or now launching the website and
promoting sales on the website,

00:19:45.000 --> 00:19:45.740
we use Facebook.

00:19:45.740 --> 00:19:48.260
And I feel like that customer
is much more into what

00:19:48.260 --> 00:19:49.860
your sales are,
what deal can I get.

00:19:49.860 --> 00:19:52.276
It's much more commerce-driven
than the visual, Instagram.

00:19:53.784 --> 00:19:54.700
LEAH CHERNIKOFF: Yeah.

00:19:54.700 --> 00:19:56.649
I would say Instagram too.

00:19:56.649 --> 00:19:58.190
And I also think
that Spring is going

00:19:58.190 --> 00:20:02.902
to be a game changer, maybe.

00:20:02.902 --> 00:20:04.610
I don't know if you
guys know what it is.

00:20:04.610 --> 00:20:07.190
But as I understand it-- and I'm
getting a walk-through tomorrow

00:20:07.190 --> 00:20:08.150
actually, of the app.

00:20:08.150 --> 00:20:11.740
But I've seen it in
its early stages too.

00:20:11.740 --> 00:20:15.780
It's like an Instagram feed,
but you can click to buy.

00:20:15.780 --> 00:20:17.660
And it's really, really
beautifully designed,

00:20:17.660 --> 00:20:19.630
and really intuitive.

00:20:19.630 --> 00:20:22.600
So, I don't shop
online that much.

00:20:22.600 --> 00:20:24.540
That one makes a
lot of sense to me.

00:20:24.540 --> 00:20:27.140
So I think that--
and every major brand

00:20:27.140 --> 00:20:29.460
is signing up with them.

00:20:29.460 --> 00:20:31.224
So I think that will be a force.

00:20:31.224 --> 00:20:32.640
But other than
that, yeah, I think

00:20:32.640 --> 00:20:34.770
Instagram is such a
great way for brands

00:20:34.770 --> 00:20:38.040
to present exactly the
image that they want.

00:20:38.040 --> 00:20:40.520
But then also you
see Style Bloggers,

00:20:40.520 --> 00:20:43.680
and I think, what is
it, Like To Know It?

00:20:43.680 --> 00:20:45.050
LAUREN SHERMAN: Like To Know It.

00:20:45.050 --> 00:20:46.966
LEAH CHERNIKOFF: I did
talk to a few bloggers.

00:20:46.966 --> 00:20:48.780
They are seeing commissions.

00:20:48.780 --> 00:20:50.145
So I think it's working too.

00:20:50.145 --> 00:20:52.667
It's another way to make
Instagram shoppable.

00:20:52.667 --> 00:20:54.250
That one seems like
more effort to me,

00:20:54.250 --> 00:20:55.333
like, you have to sign up.

00:20:55.333 --> 00:20:57.130
And then more steps.

00:20:57.130 --> 00:20:59.560
But I think, when somebody
sees something on a girl

00:20:59.560 --> 00:21:02.018
that they think looks really
cute, and they want the dress,

00:21:02.018 --> 00:21:03.600
it's a good way to get it.

00:21:03.600 --> 00:21:04.850
LAUREN SHERMAN: Yeah, I agree.

00:21:04.850 --> 00:21:07.820
Instagram and Spring-- I'm
also really excited about.

00:21:07.820 --> 00:21:10.530
I think, if anybody's
going to be able to do it--

00:21:10.530 --> 00:21:13.930
what companies like
List and I'm trying

00:21:13.930 --> 00:21:18.030
to think of what the other
ones are called, and Fancy,

00:21:18.030 --> 00:21:21.690
have tried to do with fashion
and have not been able to.

00:21:21.690 --> 00:21:24.760
I really think Spring might
have a chance to do it.

00:21:24.760 --> 00:21:28.220
Especially because it's--
they're doing partnerships.

00:21:28.220 --> 00:21:31.826
It's not affiliate-based
as I think I'm correct?

00:21:31.826 --> 00:21:33.850
STEVEN ALAN: What do you mean?

00:21:33.850 --> 00:21:35.400
Partnerships as opposed to?

00:21:35.400 --> 00:21:37.810
LAUREN SHERMAN: As opposed
to just a feed, API.

00:21:37.810 --> 00:21:38.755
STEVEN ALAN: Oh, no.

00:21:38.755 --> 00:21:39.480
It's total partnerships.

00:21:39.480 --> 00:21:39.675
LAUREN SHERMAN: Yeah.

00:21:39.675 --> 00:21:40.660
So it's not an API.

00:21:40.660 --> 00:21:43.000
So it's just very interesting.

00:21:43.000 --> 00:21:48.730
And I think that when that
launches, if it takes off,

00:21:48.730 --> 00:21:49.920
it's going to be huge.

00:21:49.920 --> 00:21:50.857
Or it will flop it.

00:21:50.857 --> 00:21:52.940
But I have a feeling it's
going to be really good.

00:21:52.940 --> 00:21:54.280
LISA GREEN: So it'll
be good, or not good.

00:21:54.280 --> 00:21:55.524
LAUREN SHERMAN: Yeah.

00:21:55.524 --> 00:21:56.940
LEAH CHERNIKOFF: But you
create the imagery, right?

00:21:56.940 --> 00:21:57.540
STEVEN ALAN: Yeah.

00:21:57.540 --> 00:21:59.140
LEAH CHERNIKOFF: So
every brands creates--

00:21:59.140 --> 00:22:00.380
like, they have
complete control.

00:22:00.380 --> 00:22:02.213
So I think that that's
part of the reason it

00:22:02.213 --> 00:22:04.290
will be so successful.

00:22:04.290 --> 00:22:06.460
LISA GREEN: So, in
that vein, do you

00:22:06.460 --> 00:22:09.810
think that there's a danger of
kind of commercializing what

00:22:09.810 --> 00:22:12.960
consumers feel like is
somewhat organic at this point?

00:22:12.960 --> 00:22:16.040
So, in the same way, like
maybe, if I think about it

00:22:16.040 --> 00:22:18.480
from a video aspect,
should brands

00:22:18.480 --> 00:22:20.090
be making their
videos more shoppable?

00:22:20.090 --> 00:22:22.980
Should there be this sort
of seamless interaction

00:22:22.980 --> 00:22:25.680
between a beautiful brand
video that you could actually

00:22:25.680 --> 00:22:26.570
click to buy?

00:22:26.570 --> 00:22:28.460
Or do you think--
because it sounds

00:22:28.460 --> 00:22:30.710
like what you guys are saying
is, Instagram's awesome.

00:22:30.710 --> 00:22:33.750
And it'll be more awesome
if you can buy from it.

00:22:33.750 --> 00:22:35.760
So do you think it's
the same with video?

00:22:35.760 --> 00:22:39.306
LAUREN SHERMAN: I don't think
many people watch fancy brand

00:22:39.306 --> 00:22:39.805
videos.

00:22:39.805 --> 00:22:41.074
LEAH CHERNIKOFF: [INAUDIBLE]
actually launched today.

00:22:41.074 --> 00:22:42.795
Cinematique, did you see that?

00:22:42.795 --> 00:22:43.670
LAUREN SHERMAN: Yeah.

00:22:43.670 --> 00:22:47.400
They've been doing stuff
on [INAUDIBLE] for a while.

00:22:47.400 --> 00:22:50.690
But it could work.

00:22:50.690 --> 00:22:51.590
And it's interesting.

00:22:51.590 --> 00:22:56.430
But I think what sells are
YouTube people, like vloggers.

00:22:56.430 --> 00:22:59.527
I think that they can really
sell product via the web.

00:22:59.527 --> 00:23:02.840
And I think on the
really high end, I mean,

00:23:02.840 --> 00:23:04.710
I think occasionally
it does work.

00:23:04.710 --> 00:23:08.897
And there are certain
viral fashion videos

00:23:08.897 --> 00:23:09.730
that have done well.

00:23:09.730 --> 00:23:12.000
And maybe if they had click
to buy on them-- like,

00:23:12.000 --> 00:23:14.100
Rachel Antonoff does
some really cool ones.

00:23:14.100 --> 00:23:17.176
If they had had click to buy,
maybe it would have done well.

00:23:17.176 --> 00:23:18.550
But I think that
that's something

00:23:18.550 --> 00:23:22.640
that bigger brands
haven't figured out yet.

00:23:22.640 --> 00:23:24.140
STEVEN ALAN: I'd
heard the other day

00:23:24.140 --> 00:23:28.740
that I think there was
15,000 people on YouTube that

00:23:28.740 --> 00:23:32.230
have a greater
following than Vogue.

00:23:32.230 --> 00:23:33.670
LAUREN SHERMAN: Oh yeah.

00:23:33.670 --> 00:23:35.240
STEVEN ALAN: It
was just amazing.

00:23:35.240 --> 00:23:37.740
LAUREN SHERMAN: Yeah, and even
if people are watching things

00:23:37.740 --> 00:23:40.550
on Vogue-- I mean, Leah
could speak to this more

00:23:40.550 --> 00:23:44.070
because I haven't been
editing a site for a while.

00:23:44.070 --> 00:23:47.530
But it's really hard to get
people to shop via editorial,

00:23:47.530 --> 00:23:49.300
when you're a really big name.

00:23:49.300 --> 00:23:51.500
If you're a blogger,
it's easier.

00:23:51.500 --> 00:23:53.350
Because they have a
closer connection.

00:23:53.350 --> 00:24:00.430
But to get someone to buy
something via a story,

00:24:00.430 --> 00:24:03.850
it's not really why people are
going to editorial websites.

00:24:03.850 --> 00:24:05.060
I don't know that's changing.

00:24:05.060 --> 00:24:06.340
Do you think it is?

00:24:06.340 --> 00:24:07.950
LEAH CHERNIKOFF: No.

00:24:07.950 --> 00:24:11.710
I think it's easier online.

00:24:11.710 --> 00:24:14.440
Because throughout the day, we
have smaller market stories.

00:24:14.440 --> 00:24:16.010
And they're much more focused.

00:24:16.010 --> 00:24:18.740
Or maybe one is really centered
around an editor who functions

00:24:18.740 --> 00:24:20.180
in that way more like a blogger.

00:24:20.180 --> 00:24:22.960
Because then you sort of
might follow that editor

00:24:22.960 --> 00:24:24.415
on their social
channels and feel

00:24:24.415 --> 00:24:25.540
a more personal connection.

00:24:25.540 --> 00:24:29.062
So if they pick the product,
maybe wear it themselves,

00:24:29.062 --> 00:24:31.020
you might be more inclined
to buy it than maybe

00:24:31.020 --> 00:24:35.410
if you just saw like a
roundup of like 100 boots.

00:24:35.410 --> 00:24:38.950
But you might get a sense of
the direction you want to go in.

00:24:38.950 --> 00:24:41.120
I still think it offers
guidance, but not

00:24:41.120 --> 00:24:44.140
in the same way of an immediate
sort of drive to sale.

00:24:44.140 --> 00:24:46.750
And then this thing that-- I got
a walk-through of Cinematique

00:24:46.750 --> 00:24:49.060
which makes shoppable videos.

00:24:49.060 --> 00:24:51.520
And it launched with
Net-a-Porter today.

00:24:51.520 --> 00:24:53.990
And I still, I mean as
someone who runs a site,

00:24:53.990 --> 00:24:56.240
it's hard to get
people to watch videos.

00:24:56.240 --> 00:25:00.880
Like, we don't have a user's
attention for very long.

00:25:00.880 --> 00:25:02.900
And so the videos
have to be short.

00:25:02.900 --> 00:25:04.560
And I think, it's
also just going to--

00:25:04.560 --> 00:25:07.900
you have to change the way users
interact with video, to let

00:25:07.900 --> 00:25:10.440
them know like, oh, you
can hover over the video

00:25:10.440 --> 00:25:11.910
and click things in.

00:25:11.910 --> 00:25:14.310
And I think that's
just not-- it's really

00:25:14.310 --> 00:25:16.550
going to have to
be a behavior shift

00:25:16.550 --> 00:25:21.010
to let people know
that that's possible.

00:25:21.010 --> 00:25:22.187
LISA GREEN: Cool.

00:25:22.187 --> 00:25:23.770
I'm going to open
it up for questions.

00:25:23.770 --> 00:25:24.950
I can keep asking them.

00:25:24.950 --> 00:25:27.830
But I don't if anybody in
the audience has anything.

00:25:27.830 --> 00:25:31.720
You can just raise your hand
if you've got any questions.

00:25:31.720 --> 00:25:33.419
Oh, OK.

00:25:33.419 --> 00:25:35.460
AUDIENCE: What do you
think is the next big thing

00:25:35.460 --> 00:25:38.298
in e-commerce in
regards to shopping?

00:25:38.298 --> 00:25:42.555
Or what would you
like to see next?

00:25:42.555 --> 00:25:44.990
LAUREN SHERMAN: I
think that beauty

00:25:44.990 --> 00:25:49.970
is something has a
lot of opportunity.

00:25:49.970 --> 00:25:52.030
There's a ton of
opportunity via YouTube

00:25:52.030 --> 00:25:54.130
and beauty, which is
already happening.

00:25:54.130 --> 00:25:57.330
But I think that the beauty
space-- a lot of beauty brands

00:25:57.330 --> 00:26:01.170
have a weird rule that if you
don't have any brick and mortar

00:26:01.170 --> 00:26:04.620
store, you can't sell
their stuff online.

00:26:04.620 --> 00:26:07.410
And someone explained to me
why that is the other day.

00:26:07.410 --> 00:26:10.800
Because every beauty person I
meet, I ask them why that is.

00:26:10.800 --> 00:26:12.960
But they're really
strict about it.

00:26:12.960 --> 00:26:16.640
So a lot of beauty sites that
don't have brick and mortar,

00:26:16.640 --> 00:26:19.270
they don't have a
lot of big brands.

00:26:19.270 --> 00:26:23.100
And I think that that's
going to start-- I mean,

00:26:23.100 --> 00:26:24.680
Amazon has everything.

00:26:24.680 --> 00:26:28.440
Because they pool from--
it's not regulated.

00:26:28.440 --> 00:26:30.760
And obviously you guys
know how that works.

00:26:30.760 --> 00:26:35.370
But I think beauty
is a huge space.

00:26:35.370 --> 00:26:39.520
It doesn't-- as much as people
say you need to try on product,

00:26:39.520 --> 00:26:43.091
people have been shopping via
Avon catalogs for 100 years

00:26:43.091 --> 00:26:43.590
or whatever.

00:26:43.590 --> 00:26:46.510
I don't think that
that's a barrier.

00:26:46.510 --> 00:26:49.030
And I think there aren't
that many big players.

00:26:49.030 --> 00:26:49.790
There's Amazon.

00:26:49.790 --> 00:26:52.420
There are the bigger websites.

00:26:52.420 --> 00:26:54.140
And there is Sephora.

00:26:54.140 --> 00:26:56.590
But there isn't a
ton in that space.

00:26:56.590 --> 00:26:59.190
And that to me, that's
what I'm looking at,

00:26:59.190 --> 00:27:03.950
at different e-commerce
opportunities in there.

00:27:03.950 --> 00:27:07.870
And I also think just the
closer connection with in-store.

00:27:07.870 --> 00:27:10.450
I mean, there was
some survey that

00:27:10.450 --> 00:27:15.580
said that people still
prefer to shop in-store.

00:27:15.580 --> 00:27:17.580
I haven't looked
at the data enough

00:27:17.580 --> 00:27:20.030
to know whether or
not it was BS or not.

00:27:20.030 --> 00:27:23.010
But I think that people
are using the web.

00:27:23.010 --> 00:27:26.920
Regardless, every
purchase is made with web.

00:27:26.920 --> 00:27:30.436
So just the closer the
connection is between the two,

00:27:30.436 --> 00:27:34.632
the better off the
retailer is, I think.

00:27:34.632 --> 00:27:38.290
LISA GREEN: You guys have
anything about e-commerce.

00:27:38.290 --> 00:27:41.620
STEVEN ALAN: I would just--
I think when 3D-- I mean,

00:27:41.620 --> 00:27:47.610
that's going to be revolutionary
in shopping, I think.

00:27:47.610 --> 00:27:50.920
And just quality
imagery in general.

00:27:50.920 --> 00:27:53.880
When we photograph things,
it's always just the lighting

00:27:53.880 --> 00:27:56.100
and being able to
really see color.

00:27:56.100 --> 00:27:57.770
So I think as
technology advances,

00:27:57.770 --> 00:28:02.017
that's going to really
help with things like that.

00:28:02.017 --> 00:28:03.600
LISA GREEN: One of
the other questions

00:28:03.600 --> 00:28:05.558
that I have which, I
haven't gotten to ask yet,

00:28:05.558 --> 00:28:08.390
which seems like a right to
ask it is, so if Google could

00:28:08.390 --> 00:28:11.950
design the perfect product for
fashion brands, what would that

00:28:11.950 --> 00:28:12.970
look like to you guys?

00:28:12.970 --> 00:28:16.140
What's missing in this space
that you think you really

00:28:16.140 --> 00:28:19.470
need to drive your sales,
or to promote your brand,

00:28:19.470 --> 00:28:21.989
or that you really think
is missing to make fashion

00:28:21.989 --> 00:28:24.030
more exciting, more
accessible, more Interesting?

00:28:27.270 --> 00:28:27.770
Leah?

00:28:27.770 --> 00:28:28.874
I'm gonna call on Leah.

00:28:28.874 --> 00:28:30.790
LEAH CHERNIKOFF: That's
a really big question.

00:28:30.790 --> 00:28:31.415
LISA GREEN: OK.

00:28:31.415 --> 00:28:33.121
Brett?

00:28:33.121 --> 00:28:35.370
BRETT HEYMAN: I'm sticking
with virtual dressing room.

00:28:35.370 --> 00:28:35.675
LISA GREEN: That's right.

00:28:35.675 --> 00:28:36.660
You nailed it.

00:28:36.660 --> 00:28:38.580
BRETT HEYMAN: It's
applicable for beauty, too.

00:28:38.580 --> 00:28:40.270
Uplighting your face,
what colors work?

00:28:40.270 --> 00:28:42.228
I just feel like that's
going to be everything.

00:28:44.888 --> 00:28:47.440
STEVEN ALAN: I think
checkout, too, is a big deal.

00:28:47.440 --> 00:28:50.350
I mean obviously,
like Amazon checkout,

00:28:50.350 --> 00:28:51.470
it just makes it so easy.

00:28:51.470 --> 00:28:54.410
But I think just
having this sort

00:28:54.410 --> 00:28:57.520
of seamless one-click
ability to do

00:28:57.520 --> 00:29:01.710
that, I think it'll
help with that.

00:29:01.710 --> 00:29:04.210
LEAH CHERNIKOFF: And making
returns as easy as possible,

00:29:04.210 --> 00:29:04.430
too.

00:29:04.430 --> 00:29:06.805
I mean, I think that's the
number one thing that stops me

00:29:06.805 --> 00:29:09.390
from shopping online is because
I know that, if I get it,

00:29:09.390 --> 00:29:11.264
and then I wait too
long, I'm screwed.

00:29:11.264 --> 00:29:11.930
And I've got it.

00:29:11.930 --> 00:29:15.460
So I tend to only make
purchases when I really

00:29:15.460 --> 00:29:17.050
know that it's
something like-- brand

00:29:17.050 --> 00:29:18.633
that I love, the
size of that fits me.

00:29:18.633 --> 00:29:20.009
And I know all
these things work.

00:29:20.009 --> 00:29:22.091
STEVEN ALAN: And you were
saying in the beginning,

00:29:22.091 --> 00:29:24.440
you were saying about
checking different sites

00:29:24.440 --> 00:29:27.384
to see who had it
at a lower price?

00:29:27.384 --> 00:29:29.800
I would think that if there
was an app that actually could

00:29:29.800 --> 00:29:32.250
do that for you, where
you just automatically

00:29:32.250 --> 00:29:35.080
have whatever the sites
that you would check.

00:29:35.080 --> 00:29:37.391
And it would just tell you, OK.

00:29:37.391 --> 00:29:37.890
Buy it.

00:29:37.890 --> 00:29:39.570
It's cheapest.

00:29:39.570 --> 00:29:40.720
LEAH CHERNIKOFF: And you would
have a definitive answer.

00:29:40.720 --> 00:29:42.595
STEVEN ALAN: So they do
it with air fare now.

00:29:42.595 --> 00:29:46.040
So it seems like, if they do
with airfare, they could do it.

00:29:46.040 --> 00:29:48.057
LISA GREEN: We have--
there's a particular brand

00:29:48.057 --> 00:29:50.390
that we work with who's in
the sort of accessible luxury

00:29:50.390 --> 00:29:50.890
space.

00:29:50.890 --> 00:29:54.550
So their goods are about
$400, kind of in that range.

00:29:54.550 --> 00:29:56.790
And what we've found
that's really interesting,

00:29:56.790 --> 00:29:59.480
that their shipping is
actually quite expensive.

00:29:59.480 --> 00:30:02.549
But for some reason, they
are still making sales,

00:30:02.549 --> 00:30:04.090
even though their
product is actually

00:30:04.090 --> 00:30:05.800
sold by other wholesalers.

00:30:05.800 --> 00:30:08.416
What do you guys make of that?

00:30:08.416 --> 00:30:09.915
We're trying to
figure out, is there

00:30:09.915 --> 00:30:12.380
a reason why you think
consumers might still

00:30:12.380 --> 00:30:15.140
prefer to buy brand-direct
versus from Shopbop

00:30:15.140 --> 00:30:20.740
or Bloomingdale's
or Steven Allan?

00:30:20.740 --> 00:30:22.380
How do you guys
sweeten the deal?

00:30:22.380 --> 00:30:24.380
How do you get people to
buy something from you,

00:30:24.380 --> 00:30:26.410
even if it's not
necessarily price?

00:30:26.410 --> 00:30:29.244
Like, why buy it
from StevenAlan.com.

00:30:29.244 --> 00:30:30.910
STEVEN ALAN: Well, I
mean, I don't know.

00:30:30.910 --> 00:30:33.120
I guess with anything,
if I'm buying a product,

00:30:33.120 --> 00:30:35.960
and it's from the source,
then I would think maybe it's

00:30:35.960 --> 00:30:36.950
in better condition.

00:30:36.950 --> 00:30:40.602
It's not coming off of
some shelf on a store,

00:30:40.602 --> 00:30:41.810
where they're wrapping it up.

00:30:41.810 --> 00:30:46.440
And if there is a problem,
that I can call that company.

00:30:46.440 --> 00:30:48.680
And they'll certainly
stand behind their product.

00:30:48.680 --> 00:30:51.370
Whereas if you're
selling another product,

00:30:51.370 --> 00:30:52.920
you can only stand
behind it-- well,

00:30:52.920 --> 00:30:54.003
you could stand behind it.

00:30:54.003 --> 00:30:56.990
But it's not always the same
as if you're buying it direct.

00:30:56.990 --> 00:31:02.229
I mean, I just-- actually
it doesn't relate.

00:31:02.229 --> 00:31:03.520
I was just thinking of pillows.

00:31:03.520 --> 00:31:04.130
Because I'm buying pillows.

00:31:04.130 --> 00:31:05.950
But I can't think of
the analogy that I

00:31:05.950 --> 00:31:07.241
wanted to think of, so, anyway.

00:31:07.241 --> 00:31:10.462
[LAUGHTER]

00:31:10.462 --> 00:31:13.560
BRETT HEYMAN: I just, for
me, I shop on Net-a-Porter

00:31:13.560 --> 00:31:15.390
because it's very expedient.

00:31:15.390 --> 00:31:16.330
Like it's fast.

00:31:16.330 --> 00:31:17.329
It's same day.

00:31:17.329 --> 00:31:19.370
That's something we offer
in New York on our site

00:31:19.370 --> 00:31:22.010
and would love to roll it out
eventually at other places.

00:31:22.010 --> 00:31:22.780
And you mentioned Spring.

00:31:22.780 --> 00:31:24.113
We just had our Spring training.

00:31:24.113 --> 00:31:27.700
And they're only offering one
mode and method of shipping.

00:31:27.700 --> 00:31:30.264
I think everybody wants things
so fast that there's not

00:31:30.264 --> 00:31:31.930
like-- you know,
normally you check out.

00:31:31.930 --> 00:31:34.600
You have ground, expedited,
et cetera, et cetera.

00:31:34.600 --> 00:31:36.210
And Spring is only
offering expedited.

00:31:36.210 --> 00:31:37.960
So I just think--

00:31:37.960 --> 00:31:39.310
STEVEN ALAN: It's also free.

00:31:39.310 --> 00:31:40.060
BRETT HEYMAN: Yes.

00:31:40.060 --> 00:31:42.712
LISA GREEN: It's free expedited.

00:31:42.712 --> 00:31:44.870
LAUREN SHERMAN: Yeah,
I think the big reason

00:31:44.870 --> 00:31:46.730
would be selection.

00:31:46.730 --> 00:31:51.080
So assume that retailer may
have one or two things on-- you

00:31:51.080 --> 00:31:54.867
can go to Edie Parker and
get probably everything

00:31:54.867 --> 00:31:56.450
that you've done
that season, plus all

00:31:56.450 --> 00:31:57.590
the personalization stuff.

00:31:57.590 --> 00:31:59.048
Whereas, if you go
on Net-a-Porter,

00:31:59.048 --> 00:32:00.800
there are probably
four SKUs or something.

00:32:00.800 --> 00:32:02.380
I think that's a
big part of it is

00:32:02.380 --> 00:32:07.460
that, I like to shop at
individual websites a lot.

00:32:07.460 --> 00:32:11.280
Because it's usually
every single product

