where you saw and realized
how important online is

00:41:50.410 --> 00:41:51.910
for the modern shopper?

00:41:54.910 --> 00:41:57.470
STEVEN ALAN: I mean,
one thing in regards

00:41:57.470 --> 00:41:59.890
to what you were saying-- I
mean, with online as opposed

00:41:59.890 --> 00:42:02.400
to print, obviously,
you can track it.

00:42:02.400 --> 00:42:05.226
So if you're a business and
you're going to advertise,

00:42:05.226 --> 00:42:07.350
and you're going to take
out an ad in the magazine,

00:42:07.350 --> 00:42:08.474
it's just sort of like, OK.

00:42:08.474 --> 00:42:09.690
Well let's hope for the best.

00:42:09.690 --> 00:42:11.410
It's like throwing darts.

00:42:11.410 --> 00:42:13.710
But online, you're
actually seeing it.

00:42:13.710 --> 00:42:17.530
You're actually seeing
the monetization

00:42:17.530 --> 00:42:19.640
of what you're doing.

00:42:19.640 --> 00:42:21.610
And I think in the
future, more companies

00:42:21.610 --> 00:42:24.930
are going to look
at more the latent

00:42:24.930 --> 00:42:26.890
demand of what's happening.

00:42:26.890 --> 00:42:29.980
In other words, let's say
you're a retailer, a designer.

00:42:29.980 --> 00:42:32.010
And you have
product on the site.

00:42:32.010 --> 00:42:36.990
And you have buy 100 smalls,
100 mediums, 100 larges.

00:42:36.990 --> 00:42:37.720
Right?

00:42:37.720 --> 00:42:38.990
And you sell all the mediums.

00:42:38.990 --> 00:42:41.029
So all you know
is, well I should

00:42:41.029 --> 00:42:42.070
have bought more mediums.

00:42:42.070 --> 00:42:43.690
Because I sold out.

00:42:43.690 --> 00:42:45.650
But I think in the
future more and more

00:42:45.650 --> 00:42:47.900
companies will start
looking at that data

00:42:47.900 --> 00:42:50.110
not as, well, I
sold 100 mediums.

00:42:50.110 --> 00:42:54.400
But 1,000 people clicked
on medium to buy it.

00:42:54.400 --> 00:42:55.770
And I only had 100.

00:42:55.770 --> 00:42:58.410
So not only did I
underbuy, but I really

00:42:58.410 --> 00:43:03.540
should start to think about
just how I bought it in general.

00:43:06.050 --> 00:43:07.639
I don't know if that--

00:43:07.639 --> 00:43:09.680
LISA GREEN: it's hard to
believe that we're still

00:43:09.680 --> 00:43:12.500
talking about people not
believing in online as just

00:43:12.500 --> 00:43:13.600
a communication channel.

00:43:13.600 --> 00:43:15.825
Is that why we're
silent, I think?

00:43:15.825 --> 00:43:17.200
LAUREN SHERMAN:
I've had to write

00:43:17.200 --> 00:43:20.520
a bunch of stories of brands
going online, and brands--

00:43:20.520 --> 00:43:22.230
why aren't brands still online?

00:43:22.230 --> 00:43:25.560
And I got online because
that's where I got a job.

00:43:25.560 --> 00:43:28.000
And what are you going to do?

00:43:28.000 --> 00:43:30.341
I wanted to work
at a Teen Vogue.

00:43:30.341 --> 00:43:31.590
And I got a job at Forbes.com.

00:43:31.590 --> 00:43:33.960
And it ended up
being great for me.

00:43:33.960 --> 00:43:38.540
But I was not excited to work
in at a financial website.

00:43:38.540 --> 00:43:41.750
And then I realized that,
oh, 30 million people just

00:43:41.750 --> 00:43:42.550
read my story.

00:43:42.550 --> 00:43:46.310
And I'm getting emails from guys
in India asking about-- like.

00:43:46.310 --> 00:43:49.540
So I think that's
when you just realize

00:43:49.540 --> 00:43:52.910
the power of the web and
the influence the web

00:43:52.910 --> 00:43:54.850
has over print.

00:43:54.850 --> 00:43:56.730
I mean, print still
has influence.

00:43:56.730 --> 00:43:57.740
And it's still smart.

00:43:57.740 --> 00:44:03.390
And I'm assuming that the brand
is at a very high price point.

00:44:03.390 --> 00:44:05.090
OK, then I don't understand it.

00:44:05.090 --> 00:44:05.760
[LAUGHTER]

00:44:05.760 --> 00:44:07.970
Like, if you're
Chanel or Celine,

00:44:07.970 --> 00:44:09.960
which are the only ones
that I can think of.

00:44:09.960 --> 00:44:11.770
I mean, they don't
really need to.

00:44:11.770 --> 00:44:16.390
Because A, maybe they
will need to someday.

00:44:16.390 --> 00:44:19.560
But they sell a
ton of-- they sell

00:44:19.560 --> 00:44:25.720
enough handbags to send
a 5,000 people to Dallas

00:44:25.720 --> 00:44:29.030
for their $500 million
show or whatever.

00:44:29.030 --> 00:44:34.310
But I think that
once you see the--

00:44:34.310 --> 00:44:35.980
are they not selling
online at all?

00:44:35.980 --> 00:44:39.667
Or they just don't want to spend
on digital advertising online?

00:44:39.667 --> 00:44:41.000
AUDIENCE: They sell [INAUDIBLE].

00:44:41.000 --> 00:44:41.400
LAUREN SHERMAN:
But they don't want

00:44:41.400 --> 00:44:43.530
to spend on digital advertising.

00:44:43.530 --> 00:44:44.770
Is that the--?

00:44:44.770 --> 00:44:45.733
Well.

00:44:45.733 --> 00:44:48.325
AUDIENCE: [INAUDIBLE].

00:44:48.325 --> 00:44:49.200
LAUREN SHERMAN: Yeah.

00:44:49.200 --> 00:44:50.370
I mean.

00:44:50.370 --> 00:44:53.570
I think you really just
need to see the power of it.

00:44:53.570 --> 00:44:56.060
Like what Steven said
about the 100 SKUs.

00:44:56.060 --> 00:44:58.390
And then 1,000
people click on it.

00:44:58.390 --> 00:45:00.844
You see how important it is.

00:45:00.844 --> 00:45:02.760
And if they're still not
getting that, I mean,

00:45:02.760 --> 00:45:04.218
I don't know what
their business is

00:45:04.218 --> 00:45:06.860
going to look like
in five years.

00:45:06.860 --> 00:45:11.820
But it's not going
to be-- I think

00:45:11.820 --> 00:45:16.690
that they need to see its
power to appreciate it.

00:45:16.690 --> 00:45:18.490
STEVEN ALAN: Also,
it's such a great tool.

00:45:18.490 --> 00:45:20.780
I mean, for me, it's
all about the product.

00:45:20.780 --> 00:45:23.690
It's about really building
this amazing product

00:45:23.690 --> 00:45:25.870
and being able to
articulate that message.

00:45:25.870 --> 00:45:29.350
So I feel like it's
enabled me as a designer

00:45:29.350 --> 00:45:34.910
to sort of reach a much
broader appeal than I could

00:45:34.910 --> 00:45:38.370
with just having stores and
let's say, if I was taking out

00:45:38.370 --> 00:45:40.750
an ad in a magazine
or something.

00:45:40.750 --> 00:45:45.060
You can really kind of dig
deeper and deeper on stuff.

00:45:45.060 --> 00:45:47.270
LISA GREEN: We've got time
for one last question.

00:45:47.270 --> 00:45:49.589
If anybody has it?

00:45:49.589 --> 00:45:52.583
AUDIENCE: I'm curious to know.

00:45:52.583 --> 00:45:55.078
So we've said a lot
in favor of online.

00:45:55.078 --> 00:45:57.074
And I'm the typical
online shopper.

00:45:57.074 --> 00:45:59.569
I buy everything online.

00:45:59.569 --> 00:46:03.062
Do you see a counter-argument
against being fully online?

00:46:03.062 --> 00:46:04.808
Do you think there's
still a place where

00:46:04.808 --> 00:46:07.054
you need to have brick
and mortar partners?

00:46:07.054 --> 00:46:09.050
And you need to have
your own storefront?

00:46:09.050 --> 00:46:11.545
Or do you think you
could very easily

00:46:11.545 --> 00:46:14.206
have your entire brand,
product line, on a website

00:46:14.206 --> 00:46:15.537
and communicate solely online?

00:46:15.537 --> 00:46:20.028
Or do you think it needs
to be kind of both?

00:46:20.028 --> 00:46:21.971
STEVEN ALAN: I mean, I
think it could exist.

00:46:21.971 --> 00:46:22.470
Certainly.

00:46:22.470 --> 00:46:23.928
I mean, there's a
lot of companies.

00:46:23.928 --> 00:46:27.300
I was talking to this
guy the other day.

00:46:27.300 --> 00:46:30.730
And the business he picked
was the sexy business

00:46:30.730 --> 00:46:32.240
of mattresses.

00:46:32.240 --> 00:46:32.870
Which is like--

00:46:32.870 --> 00:46:33.703
LISA GREEN: Pillows.

00:46:33.703 --> 00:46:34.210
Mattresses.

00:46:34.210 --> 00:46:35.790
STEVEN ALAN: Yeah.

00:46:35.790 --> 00:46:36.950
It just happens.

00:46:36.950 --> 00:46:38.500
I just happened
to meet this guy.

00:46:38.500 --> 00:46:42.270
And he decided he was going to
start a mattress company called

00:46:42.270 --> 00:46:43.470
Casper.

00:46:43.470 --> 00:46:44.585
Casper-- beds.

00:46:44.585 --> 00:46:46.070
Or Casper mattresses.

00:46:46.070 --> 00:46:47.700
And basically it's all online.

00:46:47.700 --> 00:46:50.580
And he's competing
with Sleep-Ease

00:46:50.580 --> 00:46:55.037
and all the other-- I mean,
it's a huge, huge business.

00:46:55.037 --> 00:46:56.620
And I just thought
it was interesting.

00:46:56.620 --> 00:46:58.540
Because you can't see it.

00:46:58.540 --> 00:47:01.340
So it's something that--
the mattress of all things.

00:47:01.340 --> 00:47:03.170
You want to-- you lie down.

00:47:03.170 --> 00:47:04.950
You do your test
and all that stuff.

00:47:04.950 --> 00:47:06.580
So here's an example
where they're

00:47:06.580 --> 00:47:09.600
selling a product that
traditionally has always

00:47:09.600 --> 00:47:12.520
been a touch product.

00:47:12.520 --> 00:47:14.836
And very successful with it.

00:47:14.836 --> 00:47:15.336
So anyway.

00:47:20.166 --> 00:47:22.942
BRETT HEYMAN: I know for me,
my product is so tactile,

00:47:22.942 --> 00:47:24.650
that even though we're
doing well online,

00:47:24.650 --> 00:47:26.750
I think there's still a
great benefit to people

00:47:26.750 --> 00:47:29.730
feeling the acrylic and feeling
the confetti in it and all

00:47:29.730 --> 00:47:30.810
the textures.

00:47:30.810 --> 00:47:32.650
And I mean, this is
obviously a young room.

00:47:32.650 --> 00:47:35.540
But there are people in my
mother's generation and people

00:47:35.540 --> 00:47:37.250
who are very supportive
who are still not

00:47:37.250 --> 00:47:39.330
comfortable buying
luxury online.

00:47:39.330 --> 00:47:41.400
I mean like, Amazon,
Google-- one thing.

00:47:41.400 --> 00:47:45.315
But luxury products-- they still
need to touch and feel and try.

00:47:45.315 --> 00:47:47.270
LAUREN SHERMAN: I
think menswear, too.

00:47:47.270 --> 00:47:50.610
I think guys really
want to try stuff on.

00:47:50.610 --> 00:47:52.737
Or see it.

00:47:52.737 --> 00:47:54.070
I was on Everlane the other day.

00:47:54.070 --> 00:47:55.470
And my husband
was like, I really

00:47:55.470 --> 00:47:56.720
want to try those polo shirts.

00:47:56.720 --> 00:47:58.940
But I just wish there was
somewhere I could go look.

00:47:58.940 --> 00:48:02.990
That's why I mean, Bonobos--
that's a whole other thing.

00:48:02.990 --> 00:48:04.830
Whether or not I
believe in that product,

00:48:04.830 --> 00:48:06.413
I'm not going to
talk about right now.

00:48:06.413 --> 00:48:10.600
But I do you think the idea
of going into the store

00:48:10.600 --> 00:48:12.640
and at least being
able to see it.

00:48:12.640 --> 00:48:15.840
And he said that to
me just off-handedly.

00:48:15.840 --> 00:48:17.770
And I think for
men, because they

00:48:17.770 --> 00:48:21.040
tend to buy a bunch of the
same things-- is that right?

00:48:21.040 --> 00:48:21.750
Yeah.

00:48:21.750 --> 00:48:24.990
That they need to sometimes
to see it just once in person,

00:48:24.990 --> 00:48:26.990
so they can just keep
buying it again and again.

00:48:26.990 --> 00:48:27.650
STEVEN ALAN: Yeah.

00:48:27.650 --> 00:48:29.925
LEAH CHERNIKOFF: They don't
like going into big stores.

00:48:29.925 --> 00:48:31.633
STEVEN ALAN: I don't
think it's necessary

00:48:31.633 --> 00:48:34.860
to have as many stores
as maybe in the past.

00:48:34.860 --> 00:48:37.820
I think terms of building a
brand, you would think, OK.

00:48:37.820 --> 00:48:40.380
Well you need to have all these
stores in all these cities.

00:48:40.380 --> 00:48:42.220
And I think now-- I
mean, it's definitely

00:48:42.220 --> 00:48:44.440
important to have stores
in all these key cities.

00:48:44.440 --> 00:48:48.580
But, they're kind of
supplementing that experience.

00:48:48.580 --> 00:48:52.920
So it really is a place to
sort of discover, touch.

00:48:52.920 --> 00:48:54.620
And it's OK.

00:48:54.620 --> 00:48:57.620
I think the more and more
it's seen as something that's

00:48:57.620 --> 00:48:59.380
completely OK to
go in and not buy

00:48:59.380 --> 00:49:00.963
something and just
kind of look at it.

00:49:00.963 --> 00:49:05.344
And it's sort of like
this place to explore.

00:49:05.344 --> 00:49:06.260
LISA GREEN: All right.

00:49:06.260 --> 00:49:10.280
I'll leave my final
question-- I don't need that.

00:49:10.280 --> 00:49:12.986
So we're frighteningly
already in August.

00:49:12.986 --> 00:49:14.610
And so we're kind of
hitting that slope

00:49:14.610 --> 00:49:16.560
into fall and then holiday.

00:49:16.560 --> 00:49:18.960
If each of you could
just pick one big trend

00:49:18.960 --> 00:49:22.711
that you're expecting to see
with the online, digital,

00:49:22.711 --> 00:49:24.960
retail revolution, what do
you think it's going to be?

00:49:24.960 --> 00:49:27.245
And we'll start with Brett
and go down the line.

00:49:27.245 --> 00:49:29.230
BRETT HEYMAN: Just fast.

00:49:29.230 --> 00:49:30.230
Getting everything fast.

00:49:30.230 --> 00:49:32.692
That's all I keep hearing.

00:49:32.692 --> 00:49:34.025
STEVEN ALAN: I think technology.

00:49:34.025 --> 00:49:37.100
I mean, I'm seeing a lot
more technical fabrics

00:49:37.100 --> 00:49:39.620
than I did before,
performance-based fabrics.

00:49:39.620 --> 00:49:45.970
I think people are kind of more
and more curious about that.

00:49:45.970 --> 00:49:47.772
LISA GREEN: Leah, you're up.

00:49:47.772 --> 00:49:52.230
LEAH CHERNIKOFF: Yeah,
I think speed certainly.

00:49:52.230 --> 00:49:55.076
And I mean, because--
I don't know.

00:49:55.076 --> 00:49:57.000
I do think people wait
till the last minute.

00:49:57.000 --> 00:49:58.480
I know I do.

00:49:58.480 --> 00:50:01.100
So there's that.

00:50:01.100 --> 00:50:05.492
And then if I were to name of a
product, I think the jumpsuit.

00:50:05.492 --> 00:50:07.456
Yeah.

00:50:07.456 --> 00:50:09.550
LAUREN SHERMAN: Yeah,
I think that people

00:50:09.550 --> 00:50:11.960
are just more and
more interested.

00:50:11.960 --> 00:50:14.260
And I think stores
and retailers are

00:50:14.260 --> 00:50:16.030
going to try to
do more and more.

00:50:16.030 --> 00:50:18.490
They're going to experiment
more with stuff in-store.

00:50:18.490 --> 00:50:21.360
I know a couple of stories
that are opening here

00:50:21.360 --> 00:50:24.360
in the fall that
are really trying

00:50:24.360 --> 00:50:27.890
to make the store
experience immersive.

00:50:27.890 --> 00:50:30.550
Maybe they're going
to go too far.

00:50:30.550 --> 00:50:33.540
But people are definitely
experimenting a lot

00:50:33.540 --> 00:50:35.600
with that type of
thing too, and bringing

00:50:35.600 --> 00:50:39.896
that whole multi-channel thing
into Omni channel, or whatever.

00:50:39.896 --> 00:50:40.960
I hate that word.

00:50:40.960 --> 00:50:42.002
But you know what I mean.

00:50:42.002 --> 00:50:43.584
LISA GREEN: Well
thank you guys again.

00:50:43.584 --> 00:50:45.120
I hope everybody enjoyed it.

00:50:45.120 --> 00:50:46.870
And we appreciate you
guys taking the time

00:50:46.870 --> 00:50:47.920
to come down here.

00:50:47.920 --> 00:50:50.970
[APPLAUSE]

